Learning regulatory mechanisms in the brain tissues and 7 cell types

10,293 genes are heritable in the Brain dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (tissue-level eQTL discovery)

We estimate local genetic regulatory models, fitting sparse linear Gaussian regression models with the Bayesian spike-slab prior (Carbonetto & Stephens, 2012; Mitchell & Beauchamp, 1988), including all the common variants observed within independent linkage disequilibrium (LD) blocks (Berisa & Pickrell, 2016). Of the 55,889 genes measured in the ROSMAP RNA-seq data (Mostafavi et al., 2018; Ng et al., 2017), we identify that 10,293 genes are strongly heritable with posterior inclusion probability (PIP) cutoff \(>\) 0.5; of them, 7,290 are protein coding genes according to the GENCODE version 26. Per gene, we observe strong fixed effects on average 1.53 SNPs (SD = 0.89) and nearly 34.82% of genes are robustly associated with two or more SNPs.

Our factored eQTL method identifies celltype of action in 4,532 genes (celltype-level eQTL discovery)

We can deconvolve active cell types of the tissue-level eQTL effects on 10,293 genes with our previous results on the estimated fraction of 7 brain cell types on the Brain DLPFC samples (He et al. in preparation; Mathys et al., in review). The effect size deconvolution by our factored eQTL method is almost equivalent to sub-sampling of individuals. Our deconvolution models identify clear celltype specificities on 4,532 genes out of the total heritable ones.

Jaccard coefficients of genes sharing between celltypes

Since we applied sparse Bayesian prior probability on the genetic effects of factored eQTL models. We found 3,483 genes are only active in a single cell type (76.85%). Interestingly we discovered that 1,170 out of 5,796 SNPs became newly associated with gene expressions when we applied celltype contexts.
